'''{{Lang|la|Castigat ridendo mores}}''' ({{IPA-la|kaˈstiːɡat rɪˈdɛndoː ˈmoːreːs}}) (laughing corrects morals) is a Latin phrase that generally means "one corrects customs by laughing at them," or "he corrects morals by ridicule."<ref name=Latin-Quotes>{{cite web|title=Latin Quotes: Criticism|url=http://latin-phrases.co.uk/quotes/criticism/|work=Latin Phrases & Quotes|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref> Some commentators suggest that the phrase embodies the essence of satire; in other words, the best way to change things is to point out their absurdity and laugh at them.<ref name=Commentators>{{cite web|last=Felt|first=Scott|title=Latin Phrases in Scholarly Writing|url=http://pacs.unt.edu/criminal-justice/content/latin-phrases-scholarly-writing|publisher=University of North Texas, Department of Criminal Justice|accessdate=July 11, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104034723/http://pacs.unt.edu/criminal-justice/content/latin-phrases-scholarly-writing|archivedate=November 4, 2013|df=}}</ref> French [[New Latin]] [[poet]] Abbé {{Interlanguage link multi|Jean de Santeul|fr}} (1630–1697) allegedly coined the phrase.<ref name=Santeul>{{cite web|title=Castigat ridendo mores. Jean de Santeul.|url=http://www.devoir-de-philosophie.com/dissertation-castigat-ridendo-mores-jean-santeul-139026.html|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Classical Quotations">{{cite book|last=H. King|first=W. Francis|title=Classical and Foreign Quotations: A Polyglot Manual of Historical and Literary Sayings Noted Passages in Poetry and Prose Phrases, Proverbs, and Bons Mots|year=1965|publisher=J. Whitaker & Sons, Limited|location=London|page=35|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p-0-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=jean+de+santeul+castigat+ridendo&source=bl&ots=D-TJN_t1aw&sig=nDIIXqhwFI2thYKrH7y-XCPHUXk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=wsbeUYCBE7DD4AO234DwDg&ved=0CE4Q6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=jean%20de%20santeul%20castigat%20ridendo&f=false}}</ref>

